How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:What do all humans have on the side of their head? Choices:  A: two feet B: two ears C: horns D: lay eggs E: one head<n>Output:		 All humans have at least one head<n>All humans have ears on the top of their head<n>Since all of his animals have ears, his animals also have ears<n>However, since all his animals have necks, his neck is also part of their ears or, in some animals case, it is a part of their neck<n><n>So: goats have four legs, kangaroos have two legs, cats have four legs... all of their animal will have at least one leg that is part of their head<n><n>Input:Name a group of animals consisting of a horse, a pig, a dog, a rabbit and a kitten.<n>Input: Name a group of animals consisting on three or more animals from the above: a horse, a pig and a cat, etc...<n>Output: None<n><n>Input:Name all animals with four legs and three tails.  Any that are in both tails?<n>Output: Yes: A: a hippopotamus B: a hippopotamus-triceratops C: a hippopotamus D: a hippopotamus with a triceratops E: a hippopotamus<n>So all animals are part of either three or two tails<n>Input:A: A cat B: a cat-triceratops c: a cat-triceratops d: a horse e: a horse... hmmmmm...<n>Output: A: A horse c: a cat-trico Tic-tricops d: a horse f: a dog g: a cat<n>Input: B: A dog c: a dog-trico c: a horse g: a cat hmmmmm...<n>output: B: A horse c: A dog c: A cat hmmmmm... output: B: A horse hmmmmm...<n>Input:Include an animal type (carnivores, omnivores, carnivores) and an animal age.<n>Output:A:A cat C.C.<n>Carnivores are omnivores and carnivores are omnivore and carnivore<n>Age is for animals with more than 1 leg<n>Input: A:A horse B:A horse c: A cat d: A horse<n>Output: A:A horse c:A horse d: A cat... hmmmmm... output 1: A cat D: A horse<n>in this case: B: A horse
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100. How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats. What happened to her friend?<n>Output: Julia arrived at the bus terminal after her friend dropped her off. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:What has highly criticized security? She uses 3 large stickers on the<n>front page of her journal and7 stickers each to 6 other<n>pages of her journal. Howmany stickers does Mary have<n>remaining?<n>Output: Maryadded a total of 7 stickers / page * 6pages= 7stacks<<7*6=42<<7+6=45<<7=42>>42 stickers added to 6 other pages.<n>The total stickers Mary has added is: 7 - 42 =<<7|6=45>>45 stickers.<n>Since she started off with 89 stickers, she has 89 - 42 = <<89-42=44>>44 stickers<n>left to complete the 9 page journal. How many<n>different ways is there for a person to add/remove<n>stickers to a journal.<n><n>Output: Mary added 7 stickers/page ^ 6 pages = <<7|6=42>>42 more than needed = <<7|6+45||43||44||43+44=85||8>>86 stickers to 6 other pages. One extra page left = <<7||86||85||8>>86.<n>This week she will earn 9 pages of credits for a total of 36 pages.<n>Since she started out with 89 stickers, she is now at 89-21 ---> 89 + 21 = <<89-21+21=93>>93<n>In total, Mary's total credits are 93 + 20 = <<93+20||92||92+20=123>>9.<n>So in total, she will earn 123 pages for a total of 123 + 6-20 = <-123 + 6-20 = <<83+20||91||93||90+20=124.<n><n>Input: If you cut off any piece of paper, will it fit neatly on an eight inch by ten inch sheet of paper? output: What was the original size of the page of paper on which the paper was cut?<n>

Choices:  A: michigan B: stable C: race track D: farm yard E: arizona<n>Output:		 a horse is likely to live in a stable.  We need a horse to be at least 1.5x the size of the others, so in reality, we need at least 2 horses.  We need a stable if there are more than 2 horses in the party.  To determine whether or not there are more then 2 horses, we need to know whether or not they are in stalls.  We should know where the stable is.  A race track is what you would do if you wanted to move the horses after the party.  A horse is not likely to live in a stall so the only option is a stable since the animals are separated.  If there are no horses in a stable, there should not be a barn unless it is specifically stated that some animals are housed in a barn while others live in the outdoors.  We need to know what animals are housed in which locations.  So, we need to look up a local horse racing organization that will give us a complete list of the horses housed in a given location.  Each horse gets a name, a nickname, a horse code name, and a breed.  We should add this information to each animal and divide by 3 to determine whether a horse has more than 3 legs.  We should also know the approximate size of the animals in each area.  We should also look up the population size of each area.  We can do this and make some educated guesses as to the likelihood of each location.  The more accurate the guesses, the more likely the selection will be.  We should have 3 horses with similar characteristics in these 3 areas.  We can then narrow our choices by removing animals that are in a location other than these 3 areas or horses that are more than 1/3 the size of any other horse in the area.  This way, we will know what we are looking for and hopefully have 3 to 4 horse choices.  We can then try our luck and see what we get.  The number of animals determines how many choices we get, we know that.  You can then run down the first horse you get.  Use that first horse to make more choices to determine which horses have the most likeliness of being in each location.

How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:Ice fishing can be done surprisingly far out most winters on what greatest of the Michigan's greats? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100. How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:What is a student about to do if they are sitting in front of a number of black and white keys? They will be given one more book and then the last book they can read as many times as they'd like.  They can play their piano or go to the study room to do homework.  They will need to know how to read the numbers at the top of the blackboard.  In their first reading they should learn what number looks just like the numbers on the white board.  They can then go to the study room and see if they can read any numbers off the white board. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100. Choices:  A: eat grass B: play C: kept in stables D: dominated E: drink coffee<n>Output:		 They can gather food in small amount and they are able to move to new places quickly so they cannot get much energy without their needs to be covered.  They need to stay in one place at all times.<n><n>To use a real life example. Take a horse and feed him and then let him go outside and leave him out there until he decides to eat again. Then feed him again. When he eats for the third time you give him the same treats. He only wants to eat more and more every day if he is out of food, not every other day. This is called a high gainer diet. He requires constant attention and his needs are met.<n>For our example however, we can think our way around this.<n>Suppose we have a horse named Marnie. She is a medium sized horse about 65-75 lbs. She eats just as much grass as the other horses. She loves being outside and playing. She is very good at riding, she has been ridden by professional riders. Marnie would eat more than just grass if we let her. She is a social horse so she needs to be around other horses. We will not only feed her some grass and other treats when we want her to eat some grass, we will also feed her a lot of water. She drinks it up. Water needs to be something the horse drinks so that it doesn't need to eat grass it doesn't want to eat. After a while she becomes lazy and will just stand there at the water trough without eating. When we try to give her more food she gets anxious and just doesn't want to eat any more. Over time she becomes too fat and cannot move when she is not being walked. She tires out and can't run as well. When this happens we are often forced to put her on a diet. On a diet she is still allowed to eat grass because the food helps her stay fit but her energy will always be limited. After she has eaten grass she can't go outside at the same times the other horses are outside anymore. We must put her in a stall so that she has no access to the grass.<n>We can come up with an example for many other animal types. Imagine a horse that is just too lazy, a horse that is too aggressive, or a horse that is just not able to handle his environment because of a disability. We would then need to feed the horse a high gain diet and keep him on a diet for his whole life. This is probably not as helpful as
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:What do you feel from playing football? (ex: NFL player.)<n><n>Input: What are you having trouble with? But how about the two other choices?<n><n>Input:Mary has 89 stickers. She uses 3 large stickers on the first page of her journal and the first page of each page has a single sticker. How many stickers would Mary have remaining on each of her two pages?<n>Output: Mary has 89*3=<<89*3=90>>90 stickers on her second page. In total, Mary has 89*3 - 3 = <<89-3=89>>89 stickers left. Since Mary started with 89 stickers she now has 89 - 3 = <<89>89 stickers left.<n>Since she started off with only 89 stickers on each page and added more stickers as she worked on each page, she now has 89*3 - 1 = <<89-1=89>>89 stickers<n>So the final answer for this multiple choice question is 89*3 - 1=89<n><n>Input: Mary has 89 stickers on her cover page. What can she do with them?<n>Output: Mary put 89 stickers on page 1 and 2 of the journal. How many stickers can she put on the second page of her journal?<n>Output: She put 89 stickers on page 2 AND put the extra stickers in a stack on page 1. She would then have 89 + 89 = 90 stickers, the total count on her journal.<n>Output: She put the stickers that were originally on page 1 and made a stack of them on page 1 that would have an increased number of stickers on page 1 than she could have had in previous periods. So she now has 89*1 = 89*1 = 89 stickers on her journal.<n>She put the stickers that were on her cover page and made a stack of those on page 2 that would have increased sticker counts over previous periods. So she has 89*2 = 89* 2 = 89 stickers on her covered journal.<n>She put each sticker on a different page and made a stack on each page that showed the correct amount of stickers to the left of the sticker. So she now has 87*1 = 87*1 = 87 stickers<n>The total count of stickers she put in her bound journal is 87<n>So the final answer in this multiple choice question is 87

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100. How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:The print was extremely small, as he was reading letter after letter he began to suffer eye what? Choices:  A: strain B: though C: happiness D: realization E: understanding<n>Output:		He was not reading as well as he normally did and his eyes began to hurt so he turned to the next page. He was reading much faster now since he was able to make the letters a bit larger.
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100. He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs. Choices:  A: happiness B: sore muscles C: injury D: perfection E: errors<n>Output:		 happiness<n>In this situation Mark makes two errors making his stat:<n>A: 2 errors<n>B: 2 errors<n>C: 2 errors<n>D: 2 errors<n>E: 2 errors<n>In other situations Mark makes 6 errors, the error stat is:<n>A: 12 errors<n>B: 12 errors<n>C: 12 errors<n>D: 12 errors<n>E: 12 errors<n>In the example of 6 errors, his stat:<n>A : 12 errors<n>B : 12 errors<n>C : 12 errors<n>D : 12 errors<n>E: 10 errors<n>So the final answer would be 12:6*6 = 15:15<n>So the total number of errors is 15<n>So the total negative point of this example is 4

How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:You weren't suppose to touch the wild animals, they could what? Choices:  A: lie down B: run away C: bite D: keep alive E: feel pain<n>Output:		 You were supposed to touch them only if you made them leave. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100. Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs. How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:It was breakfast time.
